The structure of uncomplexed TCR LC13 is [PDB: 1KGC]. LC13 CDR1alpha, CDR2alpha, CDR3alpha, and CDR3beta undergo marked conformational changes upon TCR binding peptide-MHC complex (details are provided in the paper).  In comparison with the unliganded structure of HLA-B8/FLRGRAYGL [PDB: 1M05], this structure of the ternary complex TCR LC13/HLA-B8/FLRGRAYGL, shows a small rigid body shift in the bound peptide. Also, HLA-B8 residue Q155 that forms a direct hydrogen bond with Y7 of the peptide in the unliganded state is displaced by Y31 of TCR alpha chain and swings away to form a hydrogen bond with T30 of TCR alpha chain.

Comments: [| P1: L1; P2: L2; P3: F3; P4: G4; P5: Y5; P6: P6; P7: V7; P8: Y8; P9: V9; |] Conformational comparison between TCR B7 with HLA-A2/Tax (this structure), TCR A6 with HLA-A2/Tax [PDB: 1AO7], the uncomplexed murine TCR 2C [PDB: 1TCR] and the uncomplexed murine TCR N15 [PDB: 1NFD] showes that both B7 and A6 bind diagonally to the MHC/Epitope complex. On the MHC/Epitope binding side, the three variable loops of the Valpha domain of the B7 are very similar to the ones of A6. Only a minor difference of 1Å exists in CDR2. The Vbeta CDR loops of B7 are rotated counterclockwise by 10 degrees and the whole Vbeta domain of B7 TCR moves closer to the MHC/Epitope complex. On the MHC-distal side of the TCR, the differences are more significant. Valpha residues are rotated 10 degrees and displaced by about 7Å. Vbeta residues are rotated 20 degrees and displaced by about 14Å. CDR2beta of B7 is tilted toward the MHC alpha1 domain. The conformation of the epitope is essentially identical in the B7 and A6 structures. The TCR pocket that binds residue C: Y5; (P5) is deep in both complexes but smaller in B7. When compared to the uncomplexed TCR structures, the B7 Cbeta chain has the same conformation and the relation between the B7 Calpha and Cbeta chains is the same.

Comments: Conformational comparison between complexes HLA-A2 with Tax(V6A) [PDB: 1QRN], HLA-A2 with Tax [PDB: 1AO7], HLA-A2 with Tax(V7R) [PDB: 1QSE], HLA-A2 with Tax(Y8A) [PDB: 1QSF] results in following. The structure of MHC alpha1 and alpha2 domains in all three Tax variant complexes is very similar. Even more similar are the structures of the MHC molecules in the Tax and Tax(A6) complexes. Most of the differences are observed in the TCR - pMHC interface where the TCR loops adopt different conformations to be accommodate for the variant epitopes. V7R and Y8A complexes have a similarly displaced CDR3beta loop. In V7R the six CDR3beta residues E: L98-G101, R102, P103; rearrange because of the large epitope residue R7 side chain. In Y8A the TCR beta subunit is tilted slightly upward. There are also differences in the cavities of the TCR molecules in the three Tax variant structures, compared to the Tax structure. The first cavity, between epitope residue P6 side chain and the alpha1-domain alpha helix of the MHC molecule, is enlarged in the P6A complex. The second cavity, above epitope position 6, is also increased in volume in the V7R complex. Lastly, in Y8A there is a new cavity, not present in the Tax complex, next to the A8 residue. In the P6A complex, there are no important structural differences because of the residue substitution. Some minor differences include the reorientation of MHC residue A: H70 and the movement of CDR residue E: L98; in order to contact TCR residue D: W101. In the Y8A complex, the CDR3beta loop residue E: E30; moves away from the epitope, and residue E: L98; moves towards CDR3alpha residue D: W101. Lastly, CDR3beta residue E: R95; is displaced.

Even more similar are the strucutres of the MHC molecules in the Tax and Tax(A6) complexes. Most of the differences are observed in the TCR - pMHC interface where the TCR loops adopt different conformations to be accommodate for the variant epitopes. V7R and Y8A complexes have a similarly displaced CDR3beta loop. In V7R the six CDR3beta residues E: L98-G101, R102, P103; rearrange because of the large epitope residue R7 side chain. In Y8A the TCR beta subunit is tilted slightly upward. There are also differences in the cavities of the TCR molecules in the three Tax variant structures, compared to the Tax structure. The first cavity, between epitope residue P6 side chain and the alpha1-domain alpha helix of the MHC molecule, is enlarged in the P6A complex. The second cavity, above epitope position 6, is also increased in volume in the V7R complex. Lastly, in Y8A there is a new cavity, not present in the Tax complex, next to the A8 residue. In the P6A complex, there are no important structural differences because of the residue substitution. Some minor differences include the reorientation of MHC residue A: H70 and the movement of CDR residue E: L98; in order to contact TCR residue D: W101. In the Y8A complex, the CDR3beta loop residue E: E30; moves away from the epitope, and residue E: L98; moves towards CDR3alpharesidue D: W101. Lastly, CDR3beta residue E: R95; is displaced.

In particular, the side chain of epitope residue C: H90;(P2) interacts with TCR residues D: Y98; and E: A103. MHC residue B: H81; interacts with TCR residue D: S95. Also, the TCR contacts the side chain of epitope residue C: F91;(P3). Lastly, the N-terminal peptide residue C: E85; (P-4) rises up towards the TCR and its main chain contacts the CDR2beta loop. Conformational comparison between complexes Ob.1A12 TCR with HLa-DR2/MBP [PDB: 1YMM] and HA1.7 TCR with HLA-DR1/HA [PDB: 1FYT] shoed the following. Ob.1A12 TCR contacts only the N-terminus of the epitope, it makes only lateral interactions with the central C: K93; epitope residue (P5) and is positioned over residue C: H90; (P2). Ob.1A12 TCR makes most of the interactions with the MHC molecule through its CDR3 loops, whereas HA1.7 TCR interacts through its CDR1 and CDR2 loops. One such example is MHC residue B: H81; which interacts with the CDR1 loop of HA1.7, but with the CDR3 loop of Ob.1A12. Lastly, the CDR loops of each TCR are localed differently. The location of the tip of the HA1.7 CDR3alpha loop differs from the one of Ob.1A12 by 15.6 Å and the location the two CDR2 loops, differs by 18.3 Å.

Comments: TCR binding: All six TCR loops interact with the MHC/epitope complex. CDR1alpha, CDR2alpha and CDR2beta loops interact almost only with the MHC heavy chain. CDR1alpha loop interacts with the MHC alpha2 helix, residues 158-166. CDR2alpha also interacts with the MHC alpha2 helix. CDR2beta loop was focused on the MHC alpha1 helix. CDR1beta, CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops interact with both the MHC and the epitope. The TCR contacts the epitope at residues 4-8, mainly through the CDR1beta and CDR3beta loops. Structural comparison between ELS4 with HLA-B*3501/EPLP (this structure), HLA-B*3501 with EPLP [PDB: 2NW3] and unbound ELS4 [PDB: 2NW2] showed that only limited conformational changes occur to the TCR, upon binding to the MHC/Epitope complex, including mainly the CDR3alpha loop which moves by 7.6Å towards the MHC alpha1 helix. No notable changes occur to the MHC, but there are a lot of rearrangements on the epitope. The TCR binding causes the bulged area of the epitope (residues 5-9) to flatten out. Epitope residue C: Q7; moves by 9Å, C: Q5; moves downward by 9Å, C: G6; moves 5.3Å towards the MHC alpha1 helix, the Calpha atom of C: L8; moves by 4.4Å and C: T9; shifts by 90 degrees towards the peptide binding groove.

Only residues P: R135, I138, E141; (P2, P5, P8) are accessible to the TCR molecule. Residue P: W140; (P7) is only partially exposed.Residue P: G131; (P–3) and C-terminal residues (P11-P13) make no contacts with neither the MHC nor the TCR. The beginning of the MHC alpha1 helix, forms a high peak and toward the N-terminus the chain runs down, away from the TCR binding surface. The epitope N-terminus points in the opposite direction, rising up toward the TCR binding surface. As a result, the extended epitope N-terminus and the MHC molecule form a broader protruding high peak. TCR binding:The TCR molecule is situated on the MHC with its longer dimension crossing the bound epitope in an orthogonal manner, instead of the usual diagonal mode. The TCR Valpha domain contacts the MHC beta1 helical region. The TCR Vbeta domain touches the MHC alpha1 helical region. Epitope residue P: R135; (P2) points upward and interacts with the main chain of TCR residues A:G99, T28;. Conformational comparison between D10 with I-Ak/CA (this structure), uncomplexed D10 [PDB: 1BWM] and I-Ad with ovalbumin [PDB: 1IAO] showed that the bound TCR structure is very similar the the uncomplexed one but the CDR3 loops have different conformations. They are closer together in the bound TCR complex. The major structural difference between I-Ak and I-Ad is seen in residues B: P65, E66, I67; of I-Ad that form a protrusion interrupting the beta-chain alpha helix.

Comments: [| P1:V1; P2: M2; P3: A3; P4: P4; P5: R5; P6: T; P7: L; P8: I; P9: L; |] The TCR/MHC interface is mostly situated on the C-terminal end of the epitope binding groove, where the three CDR loops of TCR betachain converge on epitope residue P8. The CDR1alpha loop interacts only with the MHC alpha2 helix. The CDR2beta loop interacts with the MHC/Epitope, it lays parallel to the MHC alpha1 helix and contacts epitope residue P8;. The CDR3alpha loop bridges the alpha1 and alpha2 helices of the MHC heavy chain and also contacts the epitope. The CDR3beta loop interacted with both the MHC alpha2 helix and the epitope. On the epitope side, the epitope sits deeper in the binding groove and only three residue side chains protrude from the groove (P4, P5, P8) and they all interact with the TCR. Residue P5 protruded into a pocket formed by the CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops where it made extensive contacts with the CDR3beta loop and the main chain of residue P6 interacted with the TCR. Conformational comparison between TCR KK50.4 with HLA-E/UL40 (this structure) and HLA-E with VMAPRTVLL peptide [PDB: 1MHE] showed that upon TCR binding no substantial conformational changes were observed in the MHC heavy chain or the positioning of the epitope. Only some MHC side chains showed conformational changes.

The first three epitope residues (P-3,P-2,P-1) contact the TCR Valpha domain. Epitope residues P3, P5, P6 are the residues mainly recognized by the TCR. The TCR Valpha domain interacts with the the N-terminal region of the epitope and the MHC beta1 helix. The CDR3alpha and beta loops overlay the central region of the peptide binding  groove, that contains the N-terminal part of the epitope (residues P1 to P6). The structure of the long CDR3beta is compressed into the TCR binding site by the presence of the epitope. In the 172.10 complex, the Valpha domain makes no contacts with the epitope, whereas in the D10 complex the most of the TCR epitope contacts are made by Valpha domain. Comments: [| P-3: G23; P-2: E24; P-1: L25; P1: I26; P2: G27; P3: I28; P4: L29; P5: N30; P6: A31; P7: A32; P8: K33; P9: V34; P10: P35; P11: A36; P12: D37; |] The TCR was tilted toward MHC beta-chain, contacting mostly the beta-chain and not the alpha-chain. The CDR2alpha loop contacted the MHC beta1 alpha-helix. CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops form a large, dome-shaped pocket that accommodates the side chains of epitope residues P3 and P5. Specifically, residue P3 was enveloped by the CDR3alpha loop, because its tip was 13 Å away from the tip of CDR3beta. Conformational comparison between TCR E8 with HLA-DR1/TPI (this structure), TCR E8 with HLA-DR1/TPI(mutant) [PDB:2IAM], unliganded TCR E8 [PDB: 2IAL], TCR 3A6 with DR2a/MBP [PDB: 1ZGL], TCR HA1.7 with HLA-DR1/HA [PDB: 1FYT] and HLA-DR1/TPI(mutant) [PDB: 1KLG] showed that the two E8 structures are very similar except at the substitution site (P3). All CDR loops, except CDR2beta, of the bound E8 showed substantial structural differences compared to the unbound E8. The CDR2alpha moved by 3 Å to accommodate the MHC beta1 alpha-helix and CDR3beta residues D: Y95, H96; moved by 2.7 Å. Upon TCR binding, MHC residues A: 55-59; located at the a-helix of the a1 domain, were displaced by 1.7Å toward the epitope. Little movement was observed for the epitope main chains but side chains showed large differences. The residue P3 side chain rotated by 80 degrees to contact the CDR3alpha loop. The E8 TCR is shifted toward the N-terminus of the epitope and the CDR3 loops are located directly over the epitope residue P3, whereas in the HA1.7 complex they are located over the central residue (P5) and in the 3A6 complex over the P2 residue. The locations of the tips of CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops differ between E8 HA1.7 and 3A6. The CDR3 loops of both E8 and 3A6 formed a broad pocket that accommodated two epitope residues: P3 and P5 (for the E8 complex).

The TCR interacts with the MHC/Epitope complex mostly through its alpha chain. The TCR CDR3alpha and CDR3beta are responsible for the TCR-epitope interactions. Residues P4 and P6 mediate all of the side chain contacts between TCR and epitope. The P4 residue is a primary TCR contact residue. Its side chain inserting into a deep pocket of the TCR, between the CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops. The other primary TCR contact residue P6 is inserted in a cavity that is lined by the tip of CDR3beta and CDR1beta. Conformational comparison between TCR 2C with H-2Kb/SIYR (this structure), TCR 2C with H-2Kb/dEV8 [PDB: 2CKB] and unbound TCR 2C [PDB: 1TCR] showed that the epitope conformations in the two structures are very similar. The only differences are at the P4 residue side chain and the main chain of residue P1, which protrudes more towards the TCR. Upon binding of the TCR to the MHC/Epitope complex, no gross structural changes are observed. But on the TCR-MHC/Epitope interface, the tip of the CDR3beta loop shifts by 1.7Å.

Comments: [| P-3: V1; P-2: H2; P-1: F3; P1: F4; P2: K5; P3: N6; P4: I7; P5: V8; P6: T9; P7: P10; P8: R11; P9: T12; P10: P13; P11: G14; P12: G15; |] The TCR is tilted toward the MHC beta1 alpha-helix. The CDR2beta loop is positioned directly over the N-terminal portion of the MHC alpha1 alphahelix. The CDR1beta loop is oriented away from the MHC beta1 alpha-helix and the CDR2alpha loop is too short to interact with the MHC or the epitope. Interactions between the TCR and the epitope are limited to van der Waals contacts, with only one hydrogen bond. The TCR mainly interacts with epitope residues P-1, P2, P5 and P7. The CDR3alpha interacts with the N-terminal part of the epitope. Conformational comparison between TCR 3A6 with DR2a/MBP (this structure), TCR HA1.7 with HLA-DR1/HA [PDB: 1FYT] and HLA-DR2a/MBP [PDB: 1FV1)] showed that the TCR interaction surface in the 3A6 complex is shifted toward the epitope N-terminus and toward the MHC beta1 alpha-helix, compared to the HA1.7 complex. The location of the tip of CD3alpha between  3A6 and HA1.7 differs by 12.6Å. For CDR3beta the difference is 11.5Å. Upon TCR binding the peptide binding groove widens. Also, in the MHC beta1 domain, residues 60–74 located at the bend of the alpha-helix, undergo an average displacement of 1.5Å moving away from the epitope. On the epitope side, residues P5-P10 rearrange and P7 moves to contact the TCR. Epitope residues P6 and P9 move toward the beta1 alpha-helix.

Comments: [| P-2: R-2; P-1: G-1; P0: G0; P1: A1; P2: S2; P3: Q3; P4: Y4; P5: R5; P6: P6; P7: S7; P8: Q8; |] The TCR Valpha domain is located over the N-terminus and the Vbeta domain over the epitope C-terminus. TCR-epitope interactions are mediated entirely by the CDR3 loops. Specifically, main chain atoms of CDR3 loops interact with side chains of epitope residues. TCR-MHC contacts were mediated by MHC residue side chains and not the MHC helix main chain. Conformational comparison between TCR cl19 with I-Au/MBP (this structure), TCR 1934.4 with I-Au/MBP [PDB: 2Z31], unbound 1934.4 [PDB: 2Z35] and TCR 172.10 with I-Au/MBP [PDB: 1U3H] showed that in the 1934.4 and cl19 complexes, the CDR loops conformations are very similar. The CDR1alpha and CDR2alpha loops of TCRs 1934.4, cl19 and 172.10  have also very similar conformations. These three TCRs have similar interfaces over the MHC/Epitope complex. Upon TCR binding to the MHC/Epitope complex, CDR1 and CDR2 loops had only minor conformational adjustments but CDR3 loops had larger. The tip of the CDR3beta loop moved 6.6 Å toward the epitope and the CDR3alpha loop moved toward the epitope N-terminus and underwent a conformational change. In particular, CDR3beta of 1934.4 bent inward and buried the epitope surface area from P3 to P5.

Comments: [| P1: E1; P2: Q2; P3: Y3; P4: K4; P5: F5; P6: Y6; P7: S7; P8: V8; |] The TCR alpha chain lies over the epitope N-terminal residues and the beta chain covers the epitope C-terminal residues. The TCR interacts with the side chains of epitope residues P1, P4, P6 and P7, using CDRs 1alpha, 1beta, 3alpha and 3beta. These CDRs also contact the alpha1 and alpha2 MHC helices. Specifically, CDR3beta appears to have only a very limited interaction with the epitope, at residue P6. Conformational comparison between 2C TCR with H-2-Kb/dEV8 (this structure), H-2-Kb/dEV8 [PDB: 11994422] and unliganded 2C TCR [PDB: 1TCR] showed that conformational changes are induced in three of the TCR CDR loops upon MHC/Epitope binding. CDR1alpha undergoes a hinge movement of 4.2 Å at residues A: 25-29;. Next, CDR3alpha residues A: 99-102 undergo the largest conformational change of all the CDRs. Specifically, in the unliganded structure, residue A: F100; protrudes from the tip. but in the TCR-MHC/Epitope structure, it is instead bent back by 6 Å so that the tip of the CDR interacts with the MHC alpha2 helix. Lastly, the conformation of CDR3beta is similar in the two structures, with the exception of a small segmental shift (1 to 2 Å). Comparing the liganded and unliganded MHC/Epitope complexes, the alpha1 and alpha2 helices are very similar. The epitope undergoes a main chain shift of 1.5 Å at the P5 and P6 residues.

Comments: [| P1: K1; P2: V2; P3: I3; P4: T4; P5: F5; P6: I6; P7: D7; P8: L8; |] The TCR interacts with the epitope via its CDR3alpha, CDR1beta, CDR2beta and CDR3beta loops. The epitope residues involved in TCR interactions are P2, P4, P6 and P7. MHC alpha-helical residues that contact the TCR are H: R62, Q65k Q72, K146;. Conformational comparison between KB5-C20 TCR with H-2-Kb/pKB1 (this structure), H-2-Kb/pKB1 [PDB: 1KJ3], 2C TCR with H-2-Kb/dEV8 [PDB:2CKB], BM3.3 TCR with H-2-Kb/pBM1 [PDB: 1FO0] and KB5-C20/Desire-1 Fab [PDB: 1KB5] showed that upon binding of the KB5-C20 TCR to the MHC/Epitope complex, only few conformational changes are observed on the MHC/Epitope. These are are limited to changes in the side chains of the upward-pointing MHC alpha-helical residues and a 120 degrees rotation of the side chain of epitope residue P4. Large changes occur on the TCR. The CDR3beta in the unliganded TCR has an elongated conformation with a tip made of a five residue turn corresponding to positions B: 99–103;, but in the liganded TCR, it adopts a novel S-shaped conformation made of two type I beta turns. Also, the CDR3beta shifts by 15.1 Å for the apex. Lastly, the KB5-C20 TCR also undergoes changes in Valpha/Vbeta pairing. The Vbeta domain is rotated by 8.7 degrees relative to the Valpha domain. Comparison of the KB5-C20 structure with the 2C structure, shows that the KB5-C20 TCR footprint on the MHC/Epitope complex is globally translated by 4 &Aring toward the epitope N-terminus. When compared to the BM33 structure, the KB5-C20 CDR1beta and CDR2beta loops are shifted by approximately 7 Å toward the N-terminus of the MHC alpha1 helix.

The epitope is exclusively contacted by the CDR3beta loop, whose apex folds back towards the epitope N-terminus and occupies the center of the contact interface. CDR1alpha and CDR2alpha are shifted towards the N-terminus of the MHC alpha2-helix and away from the MHC/epitope surface. There is a significant number of water molecules involved in the TCR-MHC/Epitope interface. Conformational comparison between BM3.3 TCR with H-2-Kb/pBM1 (this structure) and 2C TCR with H-2-Kb/dEV8 [PDB: 2CKB] showed that the epitope conformations are similar in the two structures. The BM3.3 uses only CDR3beta to contact the epitope, but 2C uses residues from both the Valpha and Vbeta domains. The overall footprint of the BM3.3 TCR is shifted towards the epitope C-terminus and twisted counterclockwise relative to the 2C TCR footprint.The interactions at the TCR-MHC interface in the two structures differ substantially.

Comments: [| P1: A1; P2: L2; P3: W3; P4: G4; P5: F5; P6: F6; P7: P7; P8: V8; P9: L9; |] The TCR molecule docks almost exactly perpendicular to the peptide binding groove. The variable TCR domains are positioned above the binding groove with the CDR3 loops from each chain positioned above the center of the epitope. The TCR-Epitope interactions are primarily mediated by the alpha and beta chain CDR3 loops. The CDR2alpha and CDR2beta chains make no contacts with the epitope. The side chains of the epitope central residues, P5 and P6, are oriented towards the edge onto the TCR. Conformational comparison between TCR AHIII 12.2 with HLA-A*0201/p1049 (this structure), HLA-A*0201/p1049 [PDB: 1B0G] and TCR B7 with HLA-A*0201/Tax [PDB: 1BD2] showed that the orientation of AHIII 12.2 on the MHC/epitope complex is significantly different from the other TCR molecules. Instead of the common diagonal orientation, it has an almost exactly perpendicular one. Also, there are significantly more interactions between the AHIII 12.2 and the HLA-A*0201/p1049 than in the B7 complex. Lastly, the structure of HLA-A*0201/p1049 showed no significant differences when compared to the uncomplexed MHC/Epitope structure.

Comments: [| P1: S1; P2: L2; P3: L3; P4: M4; P5: W5; P6: I6; P7: T7; P8: Q8; P9: C9; |] Residues P4 and P5 are highly solvent exposed and are the main residues interacting with the TCR. Specifically, their side chains form a large protrusion from the surface of the MHC/Epitope complex. This protrusion is enveloped by the TCR CDR loops. CDR loops contacting the epitope are CDR3alpha, CDR3beta and CDR1alpha. Residue P9 inserts into pocket F. Conformational comparison between 1G4 TCR with HLA-A2/9C (this structure), 1G4 TCR with HLA-A2/9V [PDB: 1BNQ] and unliganded 1G4 TCR [PDB: 1BNU] showed that the unliganded and liganded TCR structures reveal only relatively minor main chain shifts in all the CDRbeta loops. The largest main chain shifts in the Valpha domain also occur at the tip of the CDR3 loop resulting from a change in the main chain conformation of residues D: 95–99;. Comparing the two TCR-MHC/Epitope structures, shows that the C-terminal half of the 9C epitope is 0.6 Å further out of the MHC binding groove than the 9V epitope. On the other hand, the 9V epitope main chain in the P6–P8 region is positioned slightly deeper (0.3 Å) within the binding groove. Because of this lower position, there is a change in the TCR’s tilt, relative to an axis drawn perpendicular to the MHC/Epitope surface and the tip of the CDR3beta loop is positioned lower. The C9->V mutation caused little difference in the general orientation of the side chain within the F pocket. Also, conformational changes are found at MHC residue A: Q155; of the alpha2 helix.

The TCR binds to the MHC/Epitope complex in an orthogonal mode which is dominated by TCR-Epitope interactions, with very limited MHC-mediated interactions. The TCR is positioned over the N-terminal end of the peptide binding groove, where the Valpha domain tilts toward the alpha2-helix such that the Vbeta domain forms very few interactions with the MHC heavy chain. TCR loops CDR1alpha, CDR2alpha and CDR3alpha make the main contacts with the MHC, forming a ‘footprint’ onto the alpha2-helix (residues A: 150–158;). The movement of Gln155 caused a remodeling of P3-Tyr and P7-Trp, where the P3-Tyr rotated downwards to form a H bond with Asp156 and the P7-Trp side chain flips 180° to establish more contacts with the LC13 TCR. The mimotope and allotope mimicked the conformation of the virotope only in the ligated state and thus peptide-dependent molecular mimicry is “forced” by the LC13 TCR.

""Upon Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR ligation, the alpha-GalCer head group was observed to be shifted by approximately 1 Å. In comparison to the non-liganded Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR [PDB: 2Q86], there was a slight change in the juxta-positioning (9.5°) of the Valpha14 and Vbeta8.2 domains upon ligation. There was minimal movement in the mCD1d upon ligation, with some reorientation of side-chain conformations observed including: Arg 79, Glu 83, Lys 86, Lys 148 from mCD1d . Overall, the lack of conformational change upon Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR-mCD1d-alpha-GalCer ligation, which was also observed in the human NKT TCR-CD1d-alpha-GalCer interaction, typifies the innate characteristics of this interaction mediated by a relatively ‘rigid’ receptor-ligand binding, whereas TCRs typically show a greater degree of plasticity upon ligation with pMHC."" Detailed atomic contacts between TCR and mCD1d-alpha-GalCer are provided in Table 1 and include 10 salt bridges and 8 hydrogen bonds.

Comments: ""Like the Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR-CD1d-alpha-GalCer complex [PDB: 3HE6], the Valpha14-Vbeta7 NKT TCR (this complex) was perched above the F’-pocket of the CD1d-Ag binding cleft, interacting with a similar stretch of residues on mCD1d (76 – 87 and 145 – 153). The footprint of the two TCRs were very similar with the Valpha contacts being dictated by the CDR1alpha and CDR3alpha loops, the former exclusively contacting alpha-GalCer, while the latter making substantial contacts with both mCD1d and alpha-GalCer. However, within these common footprints, there were notable differences in the contacts made between the Vbeta7 and Vbeta8.2 NKT TCRs and CD1d-alpha-GalCer, attributable to sequence differences between the NKT TCRs and differing relative juxta-positioning of the Vbeta8.2/Vbeta7 and Valpha14 domains. In turn, these differences also altered the nature of some of the Valpha14-Jalpha18-mCD1d-alpha-GalCer interactions despite the commonality of the invariant alpha-chain between the two NKT TCRs. Structural differences at the Valpha14-Vbeta7 and Valpha14-Vbeta8.2 interfaces also “transmitted” to alterations in some of the Valpha14-Jalpha18-mCD1d contacts. Specifically, whilst many of the alpha-chain mediated contacts were similar (Table 1), differences in Jalpha18-mediated contacts were observed at the tip of the CDR3alpha loop, namely residues Asp 94alpha, Arg 95alpha, Gly 96alpha, Ser 97alpha, Leu 99alpha and Arg 103alpha."" Detailed contacts are provided in Table 1 and include 9 salt bridges and 3 hydrogen bonds.

Comments: ""Overall, the footprints of the human and mouse NKT TCRs [PDB: 3HE6, 3HE7] were similar, especially between the homologous Vbeta domains (Vbeta11 in humans and Vbeta8.2 in mouse) were compared. Within this common footprint, the following interactions were conserved between the three complexes: Pro 28alpha to alpha-GalCer; Asp 94alpha to alpha-GalCer; Asp 94alpha to Arg 79; Arg 95alpha to alpha-GalCer; Arg 95alpha to Asp 80, Arg 79 & Ser 76; Gly 96alpha to alpha-GalCer; Gly 96alpha to Asp153 (Asp 151 in human CD1d); Ser 97alpha to Val 149 (Val 147 in human CD1d); Leu 99alpha to Val 149; and Tyr 50beta to Glu 83 & Met 87. Nonetheless, a number of differences at the NKT TCR-CD1d interfaces between the three complexes were present, and these were attributable to (i) altered Valpha-Vbeta juxta-positioning (approximately 13 to 15° rotation between human and mouse NKT TCR-CD1d complexes) (ii) sequence differences between the respective CDR loops that mediated CD1d and alpha-GalCer recognition (iii) structural differences between hCD1d and mCD1d, which included an altered positioning of the alpha-GalCer galactose head group due to the presence of a neighbouring Trp 153 (Gly 155 in mCD1d) in hCD1d. Nevertheless, the alpha-galactose head group was sequestered to a similar extent in all three NKT TCR-CD1d-alpha-GalCer structures, with the preservation of the H-bond interactions to the 2’, 3’ and 4’ hydroxyl groups."" Detailed contacts for this structure are not provided.

Comments: Similar to the SB27 TCR-HLA-B*3508 wild-type in the complex with the same peptide [PDB: 1ZHL], the SB27 TCR perched atop the bulged peptide of this HLA-B*3508-AAALPEP complex. However the SB27 TCR-HLA-B*3508-AAALPEP complex shifted 8° with respect to how the SB27 TCR docked onto HLA-B*3508 wild-type, resulting in the SB27 TCR tilting more toward the alpha2-helix when bound to HLA-B*3508-AAALPEP. The SB27 TCR made very few contacts with the MHC helices of HLA-B*3508-AAALPEP, with only 3 direct hydrogen bonds and two salt bridges being made exclusively with residues on the alpha2-helix. Although a number of van der Waal contacts were made with the alpha2-helix, the interactions with the alpha1-helix were limited to one vdw contact with Arg-62. In comparison with the SB27 TCR-HLA-B*3508LPEP complex, in the HLA-B*3508-AAALPEP complex SB27 loses two direct hydrogen bonds to Gln-65 and Gln-155, and two vdw interactions with residues Gln-65 and Thr-69. However, these interactions are compensated in this complex, by additional H-bonds to Glu-166 and to Ala-158, as well as vdw interactions with Arg-62, Ala-149, Glu-161, and Gly-162.

Moreover the NKT TCR bound approximately parallel to the long axis of the CD1d-antigen-binding cleft, which is distinct from the broad range of 'diagonal' footprints observed for MHC class-I-restricted TCRs. Furthermore, of the three MHC class I positions (65, 69 and 155) that are postulated to represent conserved docking points guiding MHC-restriction, no equivalent positions are contacted in the CD1d-restricted interaction. Comments: This complex is very similar to the ternary complex of A6 with the Tax peptide, with the TCR positioning itself over HuD–HLA-A2 exactly as it does over Tax–HLA-A2, forming the same docking angle and tilt. With the exception of CDR3beta, which is shifted toward the periphery of the interface as discussed later, the loops of A6 are in the same conformation in both complexes. A6 recognition of the Tax and HuD foreign and self Ags thus proceeds with the same traditional binding mode. The difference in the TCR CDR3beta loop between the HuD and Tax complexes is maximal at the alpha carbon of Gly101beta, which in the HuD complex is moved toward the periphery of the interface by 3.3 Å. Further along the loop, Pro103beta is displaced by 2.0 Å. Although the differences in the loop between the two structures are structurally significant, in context they are not unusual, as the maximal 3.3 Å shift is just below the average CDR3beta movement tabulated in a recent comparison of free and bound TCRs. There is no obvious steric reason for the shift in CDR3beta. However, CDR3beta in A6 has been found to adopt a range of conformations in various structures with variants and mimics of the Tax peptide.

However, differences were seen in the conformation of the peptide (residues Y5 and Q7), the TCR, and most unusually, HLA-A2 (residues A: Ala150-Val152). ""Altogether, the structural data indicate that A6 forms distinctly different yet equally complementary interfaces with the Tel1p-HLA-A2 and Tax-HLA-A2 ligands. That this occurs despite a high degree of structural and sequence homology between the unligated pMHC complexes suggests the influence of a dynamic mechanism not discernible from structure alone."" The contacts are not provided in the paper.

Comments: ""The structure showed a strong tilt in TCR binding toward the DQ1 alpha1 helix, which prevented interaction of the TCR Valpha chain with the DQ1 beta1 helix. The tilt was 14.5° compared with the influenza hemagglutinin (HA306-318)-specific HA1.7 TCR [PDB: 1FYT], measured using a vector through the centers of mass of the Valpha and Vbeta domains. In addition, a small crossing angle (40°) of the TCR over the pMHC surface was observed which apparently prevented MHC engagement by the CDR1beta loop. This crossing angle was smaller than for any other studied MHC class II restricted TCR, but a similar crossing angle had been observed for the MHC class I restricted 2C TCR. As a result of the tilt and the small crossing angle, the center of mass of the Valpha domain was shifted toward the peptide by ∼6 Å compared with HA1.7, and the center of mass of the Vbeta domain was also shifted by ∼6.5 Å. The tilted position resulted in limited Hy.1B11 TCR interaction with the DQ1 beta1 helix and also substantially reduced TCR interactions with the peptide.

Comments: ""BbGL-2c shows the most significant change upon interacting with the TCR. The galactose moiety tilts toward the alpha2 helix by ∼30° (angle of the glycosidic bond), and furthermore, rotates 60° in a clockwise orientation when viewed from above. This causes the 6′ OH group to point toward the alpha1 helix instead of the alpha2 helix. Consequently, the 2′ and 3′ galactose hydroxyl groups are moved closer to the alpha2 helix to form H bonds with Asp153 of mCD1d, as has been observed for alpha-GalCer and for GalA-GSL, even without bound TCR. In contrast, the 2′ OH loses an H bond to Arg79 because it moves away from the alpha1 helix. Overall, BbGL-2c forms less extensive H bonds than either alpha-GalCer or GalA-GSL and has the biggest repositioning of the galactose group upon TCR binding, which involves the breaking of two H bonds, together with the loss of several van der Waals interactions (involving in particular residues Phe70, Tyr73, and Ser76 of mCD1d) while forming four new polar interactions."" Potential hydrogen bonds between the ligand and CD1 residues D153 and T156 are shown in Figure 3; they are not among the calculated contacts. Detailed contacts are provided in Table S1 and include 12 salt bridges and 5 hydrogen bonds between CD1 and TCR and 3 hydrogen bonds between TCR and the ligand (only two of them are among calculated contacts).

Comments: ELA peptide adopts a similar conformation to nonamer peptides with a central bulge between residues 4 and 6 [PDB: 1JHT, 1JF1].The extra residue is accommodated, not through a more prominent central bulge but by an extension of the peptide Calpha chain toward the alpha2 domain of the HLA-A*0201 binding groove. Superposition of the uncomplexed A2-ELA [PDB: 1JF1] and the MEL5-complexed A2-ELA structures shows that the peptide termini are located at virtually identical positions. This peptide conformation results in the availability of a number of residues for specific TCR contacts; these include GluP1, LeuP2, AlaP3, GlyP4, IleP5, GlyP6, IleP7, LeuP8, and ThrP9. Compared with the uncomplexed A2-ELA structure, the conformation of the ELA peptide upon docking with the TCR is very similar. There are some conformation differences in the side chains of LeuP8, and ThrP9, which adopt visually different conformations in the uncomplexed A2-ELA structure; however, these differences are within experimental error and may not represent changes in peptide conformation due to stabilization of the peptide upon TCR docking. Contacts between TCR and pMHC are provided in Table 2.

Comments: When this OCH complex was compared to alpha-GalCer complex [PDB: 3ARG], the truncated sphingosine tail of OCH did not cause a repositioning of the F′-roof of CD1d. A comparison of the CD1d-Ag binding clefts of the binary CD1d-OCH complex [PDB: 3G08] and this NKT TCR-CD1d-OCH complex showed that the spacer lipid adopted a different conformation and also showed notable displacements (>1 Å) for Leu84, Val85, Lys86, Met87, Met88, and Val149. Further, Leu84 and Leu150 in the binary CD1d-OCH structure adopted very different conformations when compared to that observed in the NKT TCR-CD1d-OCH complex. ""Although we cannot discount that these conformational differences between CD1d-OCH and NKT TCR-CD1d-OCH complexes were attributable to the spacer lipid, our results nevertheless indicated that the NKT TCR can operate via an induced-fit mechanism, whereby the NKT TCR molds the F′-pocket of the CD1d-Ag binding cleft to enable optimal engagement."" The contacts between TCR and antigen-MHC are provided in Table S3. It lists four hydrogen bonds between the antigen and the CD residues N30, G96, and R95; the last one, according to the Table S3, was not observed in [PDB: 3ARG] -- this bond was not among calculated contacts as the atomic distance appears to be too large.

Comments: Comparison of this structure with the structures of the binary A2-ALW complex [PDB: 3UTQ] and the uncomplexed 1E6 TCR [PDB: 3UTP] showed that, while plasticity of either the TCR and/or the peptide is a hallmark of the TCR-pMHC interaction, neither the 1E6 TCR nor the A2-ALW complex moved appreciably during ligation. This indicated that the 1E6 autoreactive TCR engaged the pMHC-I in a rigid ‘lock and key’ manner. The 1E6-A2-ALW interaction was unusually peptide-centric with a limited MHC contact footprint compared to other anti-pathogen TCR-pMHCI complex structures. In this structure, the 1E6 TCR formed only 2 H-bonds and 24 vdW contacts with MHC. Contacts are provided in Table 2.

Comments: The structure shows the conserved “parallel"" docking mode of the iNKT TCR on the CD1d-ligand complex. Similar to the antigens previously characterized, the TCR CDR1alpha and CDR3alpha loops exclusively mediate contacts between the TCR and the antigen. In particular, the TCR recognizes the 2′-OH and 3′-OH positions of the hexose ring via H bonds with Gly96 and Asn30 on the alpha chain, highlighting the importance of these two hydroxyl groups on the antigen in the formation of the complex. However, due to the presence of a glucose on Glc-DAG-s2, the 4′ hydroxyl group is no longer able to interact with Asn30 on the alpha chain, in contrast to other galactose-containing glycolipids.Upon TCR ligation, the glucose moiety is shifted by about 30 degrees clockwise around its glycosidic bond to assume a position at the center of the binding groove as observed for other TCR-bound glycolipid antigens. Similar to what has been described for BbGL-2c, this conformational change requires the breaking of several contacts with CD1d and the formation of new hydrogen bonds with the alpha2 helix of CD1d and the TCR alpha chain. In particular, a hydrogen bond with Arg79 on the alpha1 helix is lost while new polar contacts are formed with Asp153 and Thr156 on the alpha2 helix upon TCR binding, resulting in a final orientation conserved among alpha-linked sugars. Contacts are provided in Table S1.

Comments: The TCR interacts with the HLA-DQ8 alpha chain only via vdw contacts. The TCR adopts a standard and central docking topology over HLA-DQ8. Although the extent of contacts between the SP3.4 TCR and HLA-DQ8 is relatively small, the interaction with the alpha-I-gliadin peptide is, by comparison, more extensive, with the CDR3alpha loop and the CDR1beta, CDR2beta, and CDR3beta loops contacting positions P1-Glu, P2-Gly, P3-Ser, P5-Gln, and P8-Gln of the peptide. Of the ten H bonds present at the SP3.4 TCR-DQ8-glia-alpha1 interface, eight are mediated by peptide residues. This distribution of H bonds suggests that the largest energetic contribution to SP3.4 TCR-DQ8-glia-alpha1 binding is provided by polar interactions with the peptide. A key residue appears to be Arg110alpha of the CDR3alpha loop with its side chain oriented alongside the peptide and toward its N terminus. The guanidinium moiety of Arg110alpha packs tightly against Phe58alpha of HLA-DQ8 while also forming four H bonds to the backbone and side chains of the alpha-I-gliadin peptide (at P1-Glu and P3-Ser). In the unliganded structure [PDB: 4GG8], the CDR3alpha loop is disordered. However, upon ligation, its conformation, in particular Arg110alpha, is stabilized by an intrachain salt bridge to the adjacent Asp108alpha and by a H bond between Asp108alpha and the backbone of Arg110alpha. The P5-Gln and P8-Gln are the prominent upward-facing residues of the gliadin peptide, with the CDR3beta loop being positioned in between these two residues and P8-Gln having to reorientate its side chain to accommodate the CDR3beta loop. P5-Gln contacts the CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops of the SP3.4 TCR, forming a H bond with the main chain of Arg110alpha and vdw contacts with Ser 111beta. P8-Gln contacts the CDR1beta, CDR2beta, and the CDR3beta loops and forms H bonds with the main chain of Val108beta and side chain of Tyr57beta, from the CDR3beta and CDR2beta loops, respectively, as well as vdw contacts with Ala109beta and Leu37beta from the CDR3beta and CDR1beta loops, respectively.

Comments: Contacts are provided in Figure 5 in comparison with the human iNKT TCR–CD1d–alphaGalCer complex [PDB: 3HUJ]. The LPC-reactive iNKT TCR (iNKT-LPC) has a counter-clockwise rotation in relation to the iNKT TCR of the alphaGalCer complex, resulting in shifts of all CDR loops except the CDR3alpha. The positioning of the CDR3alpha loop, as well as many of the contacts established with the CD1d surface, is conserved across the two complexes. Of the 31 contacts that the iNKT-LPC CDR3alpha loop makes with CD1d, 20 (~65%) of these are identical to contacts made by the CDR3alpha loop of the iNKT TCR in the CD1d/alphaGalCer structure. A notable difference in our structure is that the CDR3alpha loop does not contact the LPC ligand. Another key interaction of the iNKT TCR with CD1d–LPC is found in the HV4alpha loop. This loop is typically not involved in ligand recognition in conventional alphabetaTCR and MHCp interactions. Here, the HV4alpha loop appears to play a pivotal role in LPC recognition with the establishment of a salt bridge between the HV4alpha's K70 and the phosphate of the phosphorylcholine headgroup. This interaction likely compensates for the breaking of the salt bridge with CD1d's Arg79 coordinating LPC in the unliganded CD1d–LPC structure.

Comments: Surprisingly, considering the essential role of the terminal sugar of iGb3 in determining its antigenicity, contacts between the Ag and the TCR alpha-chain involve only the beta-Glc and beta-Gal sugars, but not the terminal alpha-Gal. In addition, unlike any previously characterized exogenous iNKT cell Ag, all three CDR loops from the Valpha14 chain are involved in contacting the iGb3 molecule. In particular, Gly96 and Asn30 on the CDR3alpha and CDR1alpha loops, respectively, form H-bonds with the 2′ and 3′ hydroxyl groups of beta-Glc. At the same time, the carbonyl group of both Asn30 on CDR1alpha and Val50 on CDR2alpha, as well as the framework residue Lys68, is interacting with the 6″-OH of the beta-Gal residue. Superposition of the two structures of the mCD1d–iGb3 complex in free [PDB: 2Q7Y] and TCR-bound form (this structure, on mCD1d shows how the TCR is able to squash the trisaccharide head group of iGb3 over the alpha2 helix of CD1d while maintaining the position of the ceramide backbone in a relatively conserved orientation.

Comments: As exemplified by the SB27 and CA5 TCR-HLA-B*35:08LPEP complexes, a bulged and rigid peptide bound within the Ag-binding cleft acts a “hurdle” for the TCR to dock extensively onto the HLA itself. However, the SB47 TCR overcomes this hurdle by adopting a markedly shifted N-terminal footprint, whose center of gravity differs markedly (by 18 Å) compared with that of the SB27 TCR. Remarkably, only one HLA-B*35:08 contact point was shared between the SB47 and CA5 TCRs (Gly162) [PDB: 4JRX], and the SB47 and SB27 TCRs (Gln65); moreover, different CDR loops were involved in these contacts. Contacts are provided in Table S4.

Comments: There is a high level of similarity between the MEL5-A2-ELA [PDB: 3HG1] and alpha24beta17-A2-ELA complexes, suggesting that the overall conformation was not substantially affected by the mutations in alpha24beta17. The crossing angle of both TCRs (48° for MEL5 and 42° for alpha24beta17) was similar and fell within the previously observed range for TCR-pMHC complexes. The positioning of the complementarity-determining region (CDR)-loops over the A2-ELA surface was also similar for both TCRs. Importantly, the ELA peptide conformation was virtually identical in both complexes, discounting the possibility that changes in peptide structure contributed to the affinity enhancement. Thus, differences in binding affinity between the MEL5 and alpha24beta17 TCRs could not be explained by a large conformational change in geometry, in agreement with the authors' previously published observations. Contacts are provided in Suppl. Table S3.

Specifically, two tyrosine residues in the CDR2beta loop (Tyr48 and Tyr50) contacted a focused stretch of the alpha1 helix of CD1d, whereas the CDR3alpha loop bridged the CD1d antigen-binding cleft. Comments: The first two sugar moieties of the epitope adopted a conformation very similar to that of iGb3 [PDB: 3SCM]. Similarly, the electron density for the Gb3 headgroup was distinct; the first two sugar moieties adopted a conformation very similar to that of iGb3 in the auto-Valpha14 NKT cell TCR–CD1d–iGb3 complex [PDB: 3SCM]. However, as a result of the terminal alpha1-4 linkage, the third sugar moiety of Gb3 extended away from, and made limited contacts with, CD1d. Accordingly, these data indicate that the antigenicity of beta-linked NKT cell agonists can be attributed to induced interactions with CD1d rather than to direct interactions between the antigen and the NKT cell TCR itself. Comments: Similar to alpha-GalCer [PDB: 3HE6], the galactose moiety of both glycolipids forms H-bonds with the TCR through the 2′′- and 3′′-OH groups, whereas the 4′′-OH group loses this contact. Of interest, it has been shown that the TCR contact with the 4′′-OH group is the key determinant in TCR interaction. However, both PyrC-alpha-GalCer and 4ClPhC-alpha-GalCer lost the H-bond [while still making a van der Waals (VDW) contact with 3.5–3.8 Å distance] and still have similar binding affinities compared with alpha-GalCer, suggesting that the 6′′-OH modifications compensate in part for the loss of the 4′′-OH H-bond with the TCR. Most surprisingly, major VDW interactions were observed between the pyridine of PyrC-alpha-GalCer and the Gln52 of the TCR. The pyridine makes intimate contacts with Gln52 (distance 3.3–3.5 Å) compared with 6.4–6.9 Å for the 4Cl-phenyl group (4ClPhC-alpha-GalCer) and 8.0–12.9 Å for the naphthyl group (NU-alpha-GalCer). As a result, the TCR exhibits many more interactions with PyrC-alpha-GalCer [PDB: 4IRS] than with 4ClPhC-alpha-GalCer (this structure) or NU-alpha-GalCer [PDB: 3QUZ], leading to the observed high-affinity TCR binding. Even though the pyridine ring forms extra contacts with Gln52 of the TCR, the binding affinity does not exceed the binding affinity of mTCR to alpha-GalCer-CD1d, likely because it lacks the important H-bond between the 4′′-OH of galactose and Asn30 of the TCR. Interestingly, the additional glycolipid contact with TCR residue Gln52 has previously not been seen in any other structure. Therefore, our data provide a structural framework for the design of novel alpha-GalCer analogs that target Gln52 to increase TCR contacts.

As a result, the TCR exhibits many more interactions with PyrC-alpha-GalCer than with 4ClPhC-alpha-GalCer or NU-alpha-GalCer, leading to the observed high-affinity TCR binding. Even though the pyridine ring forms extra contacts with Gln52 of the TCR, the binding affinity does not exceed the binding affinity of mTCR to alpha-GalCer-CD1d, likely because it lacks the important H-bond between the 4′′-OH of galactose and Asn30 of the TCR. Interestingly, the additional glycolipid contact with TCR residue Gln52 has previously not been seen in any other structure. Therefore, our data provide a structural framework for the design of novel alpha-GalCer analogs that target Gln52 to increase TCR contacts.

Comments: ""The overall structure of the CD1d-SMC124-iNKT TCR complex is consistent with the structure of previously described CD1d-lipid-iNKT TCR complexes. The TCR docks in a parallel orientation on top of the CD1d antigen binding groove, deviating significantly from the diagonal footprint generally observed for MHC-peptides-TCR complexes. The interaction of the TCR with CD1d is mediated by residues in the CDR3alpha and CDR2beta loops and a CDR3beta-dependent contact, as observed for other ternary complexes obtained using the same iNKT TCR construct. Well-defined density is observed to correspond to the SMC124 molecule, suggesting an overall ordered conformation of the ligand in the binding groove, with its galactose moiety exposed for recognition by the TCR. Several polar interactions between the polar moieties of the ligand and CD1d, involving residues Glu80, Glu15, and Thr156, contribute to the stabilization of the SMC124 conformation at the top of the binding groove. Similarly, conserved hydrogen bonds with CDR1alpha and CDR3alpha residues determine the modality of interaction of the SMC124 galactose moiety with the iNKT TCR, as previously observed for alphaGalCer and other galactose-containing glycolipids."" CD1d-epitope(SMC124) contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 1.

Comments: The 9C2 gammadelta TCR docked orthogonally (87°) over the extreme end of the A′ pocket of CD1d in the gammadelta TCR–CD1d–alpha-GalCer ternary complex. In contrast, all type I NKT TCRs dock in a parallel manner (20°) over the F′ pocket of CD1d, regardless of the identity of the antigen bound in the CD1d cleft [PDB: 2PO6]. As such, there were essentially no common CD1d interacting residues underpinning the gammadelta TCR and type I NKT TCR footprints, with the center of gravity between these two TCRs atop CD1d being approximately 28 Å and 41 Å apart for the Vdelta-Valpha and Vgamma-Vbeta domains, respectively. The mode of gammadelta TCR–CD1d recognition was more reminiscent of how a recently described mouse type II NKT TCR (XV19) docked onto CD1d-sulfatide or CD1d-lysosulfatide [PDB: 4EI5]. The XV19 TCR sat above the A′ pocket of CD1d in an orthogonal docking mode (100°), although the gammadelta TCR was located even further toward the extreme pole of the A′ pocket. Thus, the gammadelta TCR docked onto CD1d-antigen in a distinct manner compared to type I and type II NKT TCR–CD1d recognition thereby highlighting the diverse mechanism by which the alphabeta TCR and gammadelta TCR lineages can interact with CD1d-antigen. Supplementary Table 2 provides 9C2 TCR contacts with CD1d/alpha-GalCer.

In fact, the interaction chemistries of each of the four peptides with the 42F3 CDR3s were nearly entirely distinct, ranging from largely hydrophobic (p3A1 and QL9) to polar-hydrophobic (p5E8) to charged (p4B10), highlighting a remarkable ability of a single binding site to accommodate a range of structural chemistries. Of particular note are unexpected conformations of the p5E8 and p3A1 peptides, which contain either a Trp or Leu substitution at P6, respectively (P6 is Pro in QL9). In p5E8, the peptide backbone has flipped, such that P6-Trp is now an up-facing TCR contact instead of a down-facing MHC anchor, apparently because of a lack of space for the Trp side chain in the H2-Ld peptide binding groove. The p5E8 P5-Phe, a TCR contact in QL9, is flipped down into the MHC anchor pocket previously filled with the QL9 P6-Pro. Thus, the TCR epitope of the MHC contact peptide is completely altered even though none of the TCR contact residues were randomized in this library. These observations highlight the unpredictable manifestations of peptide substitutions on T cell recognition and that MHC anchors can greatly impact the TCR epitope in unexpected fashions. Superposition of the four TCR structures from the complexes shows that CDR3 conformational variability in 42F3 primarily lies in CDR3alpha, not CDR3beta. Comments: ""Overall, the docking mode of the MAIT TCR is highly similar to that observed with bovine MR1 [PDB: 4IIQ] and human MR1 [PDB: 4L4V], with the MAIT TCR docking in a diagonal orientation with respect to the alpha1 and alpha2 helixes of hbMR1. The alpha-chain CDR loops of the MAIT TCR mostly contact residues of the alpha2 helix of hbMR1, whereas the beta-chain is biased toward the alpha1 helix of hbMR1. These contacts, with the exception of those made with the three bovine-specific amino acids (A72, R147, and Q151), are remarkably similar between this complex and our previously reported MAIT/bMR1 complex [PDB: 4IIQ]. Moreover, the TCR docking of both of these complexes superimpose almost identically on the recently published human MAIT/MR1/RL-6-Me-7-OH complex [PDB: 4L4V], further validating the evolutionary conservation of MAIT TCR recognition across species."" The comparison of this structure with the structure of the F7 MAIT TCR in complex with bMR1/rRL-6-CH2OH showed a small conformational shift of the CDR3beta loop, resulting in a hydrogen bond between Gly98beta and the Trp69 side chain of hbMR1. hbMR1 does not change substantially upon presentation of a stimulatory ligand or upon engagement of a MAIT TCR. The contacts are given in Table II. However, MHC residues interacting with epitope (C: Y7, F8, R9, S24, K43, Y62, W69, R94, I96, Y152, Q153, W156) and MHC residues interacting with TCR (C: R61, Y62, Q64, L65, R67, W69, M72, H148, G149, L151, Y152, K154, N155, W156, E160, W164;) do not correspond the numbering in PDB.

Comments: Apart from ligand-specific interactions, the MAIT TCR–MR1–epitope complex was virtually identical to the MAIT TCR-MR1–6FP complex [PDB: 4L4T]. Key differences between the complexes included that there was no direct contact between the MAIT TCR and 6-FP, whereas the epitope RL-6-Me-7-OH directly contacts the MAIT TCR. First, while 6-FP formed a Schiff base with Lys43, RL-6-Me-7-OH was non-covalently bound within MR1, which resulted in Lys43 drifting away from the ligand. Second, and surprisingly, the orientation of RL-6-Me-7-OH within the aromatic cradle of MR1 differed dramatically from that of 6-FP. Namely, RL-6-Me-7-OH is rotated ~75° with respect to 6-FP, such that the MR1-mediated contacts between the respective ring systems differ between 6-FP and RL-6-Me-7-OH. The tilted conformation causes the ribityl moiety of RL-6-Me-7-OH to lean towards, and form a series of H-bonds with, Arg9 and Arg94, two evolutionarily conserved residues found within MR1. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table S2.

Comments: The TK3 TCR docked at ∼66° across the long axis of the HLA-B*3501HPVG complex and thus falls within the range of roughly conserved docking orientations previously observed in TCR–pMHC complexes. The structure of HLA-B*3501/epitope in the nonliganded state [PDB: 2FYY] was compared to the current structure to determine the conformational changes that took place in HLA-B*3501 upon complexation with the TK3 TCR. Although the overall conformation of HLA-B*3501 remained relatively rigid upon ligation (root mean square deviation = 0.4 Å), several HLA-B*3501 residues changed conformation to avoid clashes with or to form specificity-governing contacts with the TK3 TCR. These included Arg151 and Gln155 and within the alpha1 helix, there were five MHC residues (Asp61, Arg62, Gln65, Gln72, and Gln76) that changed conformation upon TK3 TCR ligation. In the nonliganded state, the central region (residues 5–8) of the epitope was highly mobile within the antigen-binding cleft of HLA-B*3501 [PDB: 2FYY]. Upon TK3 TCR ligation, this region of the peptide was stabilized. Contacts are provided in Tables S2 and S3.

Comments: The aromatic pyrimidine ring systems of 5-OP-RU (this structure) and 5-OE-RU [PDB: 4NQE] superposed on the corresponding ring from the bicyclic lumazine 7-hydroxy-6-methyl-8-d-ribityllumazine (RL-6-Me-7-OH) [PDB: 4L4V]. The creation of 5-OP-RU or 5-OE-RU generated an aliphatic moiety that burrowed into the MR1 cleft, within which the residual carbonyl group formed a Schiff base with Lys 43 of MR1. This aliphatic moiety was also stabilized in the cleft by interactions with Tyr 7 and Tyr 62. By contrast, RL-6-Me-7-OH was non-covalently bound within MR1. Moreover, RL-6-Me-7-OH does not have the propensity to tautomerize into a single-ring pyrimidine system owing to its ability to form a very stable amide tautomer. Nevertheless, the ribityl moieties of 5-OP-RU, 5-OE-RU and RL-6-Me-7-OH were all located in essentially identical positions within their respective complexes, each forming a hydrogen bond to Tyr 95alpha of the MAIT TCR. Notably, 5-OP-RU and 5-OE-RU are relatively unstable in aqueous media and thus MR1 can capture and stabilize pyrimidine intermediates in the synthesis of lumazines.

Comments: The aromatic pyrimidine ring systems of 5-OP-RU [PDB: 4NQC] and 5-OE-RU (this structure) superposed on the corresponding ring from the bicyclic lumazine 7-hydroxy-6-methyl-8-d-ribityllumazine (RL-6-Me-7-OH) [PDB: 4L4V]. The creation of 5-OP-RU or 5-OE-RU generated an aliphatic moiety that burrowed into the MR1 cleft, within which the residual carbonyl group formed a Schiff base with Lys 43 of MR1. This aliphatic moiety was also stabilized in the cleft by interactions with Tyr 7 and Tyr 62. By contrast, RL-6-Me-7-OH was non-covalently bound within MR1. Moreover, RL-6-Me-7-OH does not have the propensity to tautomerize into a single-ring pyrimidine system owing to its ability to form a very stable amide tautomer. Nevertheless, the ribityl moieties of 5-OP-RU, 5-OE-RU and RL-6-Me-7-OH were all located in essentially identical positions within their respective complexes, each forming a hydrogen bond to Tyr 95alpha of the MAIT TCR. Notably, 5-OP-RU and 5-OE-RU are relatively unstable in aqueous media and thus MR1 can capture and stabilize pyrimidine intermediates in the synthesis of lumazines.

Comments: The S2 TCR docked centrally over HLA-DQ2 at approximately 80° across the antigen-binding cleft, where the Valpha and Vbeta chains of the S2 TCR sat above the beta- and alpha-helix of HLA-DQ2, respectively, thereby adopting the standard TCR-pMHC docking geometry. The interactions with the DQ2.5-glia-alpha1a determinant were unusual in that the central region of this peptide was devoid of contacts with the S2 TCR. This observation was largely attributable to a central void at the interface that was created by the CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops and a featureless central region of the DQ2.5-glia-alpha1a peptide. Indeed, the proline-rich nature of the DQ2.5-glia-alpha1a epitope lends itself toward a mostly featureless determinant. Here the P7 leucine lay flat and was oriented toward the HLA-DQ2 beta-chain helix, and thus the observation that substitution of the P7 leucine with alanine abrogates TCR recognition is most likely attributable to indirect structural effects. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 1.

Comments: The structures of the S16 TCR (this structure), D2 TCR [PDB: 4OZG] or JR5.1 TCR [PDB: 4OZF] in a ternary complex with HLA-DQ2.5-glia-alpha2 were compared. These three TCRs possess differing CDR3 loops. The D2 TCR and S16 TCRs docked very similarly onto HLA-DQ2.5-alpha-glia2, with an overall r.m.s. deviation between the complexes of 0.8 Å^2 and with the interatomic contacts mediated by the CDR1 and CDR2 loops are largely conserved. Moreover the shorter CDR3alpha loop of the D2 TCR does not appreciably affect its footprint on HLA-DQ2.5-glia-alpha2. The CDR3beta-mediated contacts of the D2 TCR were more extensive (41% BSA) than those of the S16 TCR (11% BSA). Whereas the CDR3alpha loop of the JR5.1 TCR was the same length as that of the D2 TCR, the CDR3beta loop of the JR5.1 TCR was two residues longer than those of the S16 and D2 TCRs. This variation in CDR3beta loop length had a surprising impact on HLA-DQ2.5-glia-alpha2 recognition. The corresponding Vbeta chains of the JR5.1, S16 and D2 TCRs are located equivalently, and although the interactions with Tyr55beta are lost in the JR5.1 TCR ternary complex, the interactions mediated by Thr37beta, Gln57beta and Pro66beta are nevertheless largely conserved. However, the corresponding Valpha chains of the JR5.1, S16 and D2 TCRs were not located equivalently. Here, the JR5.1 TCR was lifted away from HLA-DQ2.5-glia-alpha2, and thus the extent of contacts mediated by the alpha-chain of the JR5.1 TCR was markedly diminished. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 2.

Comments: The 3B TCR bound canonically, with the TCR CDRs contacting the pMHC surface in a diagonal docking geometry (43.4°) as previously reported for other TCR–pMHC complexes. The 3B TCR broadly contacted the MHC surface (123 total contacts with 22 different MHC residues) with only 33 contacts made between the TCR and peptide. The TI8 peptide, being an 8-mer (the shortest length reported for natural MHCI binding peptides) lacked any prominent central bulge and was almost flat in the binding groove, akin to MHC class II peptide presentation. The consequences of this flat binding mode were 2-fold. First, the 3B TCR made only 33 contacts with the peptide, fewer than typically observed for other TCR-pMHCI structures. Second, the lack of peptide bulge enabled the TCR to form a closer interaction with the MHC surface. These observations demonstrate how the length of the peptide can govern pMHC interactions. Contacts are provided in Supplemental Table III.

The 14.C6 TCR CDR1alpha loop makes extensive contacts with the P2 and P5 positions of the 3K peptide, as well as the I-Ab ß-chain residue ßH81. Namely, the TK3 TCR adopted a diagonal docking mode onto HLA-B*35:08-HPVG-D5 (66°). The main differences between the two ternary complexes were centered on the P5 position of the peptide. In HLA-B*35:08-HPVG, Arg-156 is part of a polar network that includes Arg-97 and P5-Glu, whereas in HLA-B*35:08-HPVG-D5, this polar network was weakened due to the shorter side chain of P5-Asp. Upon TK3 TCR binding, the HPVG-D5 was pushed toward the alpha2-helix of HLA-B*35:08 by the CDR3alpha loop in a manner similar to the TK3 TCR-induced HPVG peptide movement. In comparison to the P5-Glu residue, the shorter P5-Asp residue was positioned 1 Å deeper into the cleft upon TK3 TCR ligation, which caused Arg-97 to shift away from the peptide and interact with the Asp-114 and Tyr-74, as seen in HLA-B*35:01-HPVG complex. However, the longer P5-Glu residue does not allow these conformational readjustments in HLA-B*35:08 upon TK3 engagement. Accordingly, the HLA-B*35:08-HPVG-D5 complex appeared intrinsically more malleable than the HLA-B*35:08-HPVG complex, which resulted in improved recognition by the TK3 TCR.

Comparison of the HLA-B*35:08-HPVG structures in its free [PDB: 2F23] and TK3 TCR-bound forms revealed that the HPVG peptide changed conformation markedly upon TCR ligation. In the binary HLA-B*35:08-HPVG complex, the HPVG peptide leaned toward the alpha1-helix of HLA-B*35:08, and upon TK3 TCR binding, the central region (P7-Asp to P9-Phe) of the peptide was pushed toward the alpha2-helix, with a maximal displacement of 3.5 Å of the P8-Tyr Calpha atom. A notable feature of the TK3 TCR-HLA-B*35:08-HPVG complex is that the peptide adopted the same conformation as that observed in the TK3 TCR-HLA-B*35:01-HPVG complex (r.m.s.d. of 0.18 Å) despite marked differences observed in their binary complexes.

Comments: When the epitope/H-2-IEk complex was aligned with the previously solved 226 TCR-MCC-I-Ek complex structure [PDB: 3QIU], very little deviation in overall TCR-pMHC complex geometry was observed. Because the 5cc7-MCC-I-Ek complex is not solved, 5c1 and 5c2 were compared to 226-MCC-I-Ek, which shares the TCRbeta chain with 5cc7 and therefore likely retains a close footprint. The contacts between TCR germline-derived CDR1/2 loops and MHC helices, which make up roughly 50% of the binding interface between TCR and pMHC, were essentially unchanged in the new peptide complexes versus MCC.  The epitope is recognized essentially identically by 5cc7 as 5c1 [PDB: 4P2R] despite the substitution of P5 to Arg. The substitution of a bulkier side chain at P8 (Phe instead of Thr) results in a rocking of 5cc7 such that the TCR Cbeta FG loop is translated by 15 Å relative to the 226-MCC structure.

Because the 5cc7-MCC-I-Ek complex is not solved, 5c1 and 5c2 were compared to 226-MCC-I-Ek, which shares the TCRbeta chain with 5cc7 and therefore likely retains a close footprint. Comments: The structures of the epitope-HLA-DP2 complex [PDB: 4P4R and 4P57] were compared to that bound to AV22 TCR in the presence of Be2+ (this structure). Upon Be2+ binding, the DP2-M2 acidic pocket undergoes a conformational rearrangement in order to capture the Be2+ and an accompanying Na+ cation through a network of interactions via the beta69E carboxylates and other DP2 and M2 oxygens, thus dramatically increasing the thermal stability of the complex. There are two unexpected features of this complex. First, the Be2+ moiety captured is the Be2+ cation itself, not a larger complex of Be2+ already partially ligated by solvent-derived electron donors (water, hydroxyl, carbonate, etc.). Second, both the Be2+ and Na+ are not accessible on the surface of the complex, so that the AV22 TCR must recognize some change in the complex surface induced indirectly by the Be2+ and Na+. The AV22 TCR takes the usual diagonal orientation on the DP2 complex (Figure 4A), but the TCR is tilted toward the DP2 beta chain helix resulting in extensive contact with the entire length of the M2 peptide and DP2 beta chain helix, at the expense of the DP2 alpha chain helix. Furthermore, atypically, the hypervariable CDR3 loops of the TCR dominate the binding, providing almost three quarters of the contacts with the ligand. The CDR1 and CDR2 loops of the TCR contribute little to the interface. The contacts are listed in Table 1 and Table S2.

The CDR3beta loops of the B-B10 and B-F3-C1 TCRs did not alter significantly between the MR1–Ac-6-FP and MR1–5-OP-RU complexes. However, the presence of the additional ribityl moiety caused moderate and marked conformational changes within the CDR3beta loop of the C-A11 and C-C10 MAIT TCRs, respectively. The data demonstrate that the flexible CDR3beta loop of the MAIT TCR can fine-tune its interactions and responsiveness to MR1 in an Ag-dependent manner.

Comments: The docking orientation of the DMF5 alphaD26Y/ßL98W TCR was conserved when compared to the wild-type complex [PDB: 3QDG], with a TCR-pMHC crossing angle of 32°, versus 33° for the wild-type. Essentially no perturbations of the interface CDR loops or peptide were observed, indicating that our relatively conservative design strategy of selecting point substitutions against a fixed pMHC structure did not substantially alter the interface or proximal side chains. Both the tyrosine and tryptophan mutant side chains directly contact the MART-1 peptide in the alphaD26Y/betaL98W structure, and make more extensive peptide contacts than their wild-type counterparts. These mutations led to a 5% increase in buried solvent accessible surface area for the pMHC, from 1059 Å^2 to 1113 Å^2. Unexpectedly, a water-mediated hydrogen bond to the peptide was introduced between the mutant residue alphaY26 and the side chain of the N-terminal glutamate of the peptide, in addition to a direct hydrogen bond between side chains. This polar network may explain the superior affinity of alphaY26 versus alphaW26 for ELA/HLA-A2.

Comments: The structures of the DMF4 TCR bound to the MART-1 nonamer [PDB: 3QEQ] and decamer (this structure) peptide/HLA-A2 complexes showed that the TCR binds the two ligands differently. When the HLA-A2 peptide-binding domains in the two structures are superimposed, the root mean square deviation (RMSD) between the TCR variable domains is 5.1 Å. Viewed from the top through the TCR, each loop, with the exception of CDR3ß, is arranged differently over the pMHCs. This is reflected in a 15 ̊ difference in docking angle, with the TCR positioned more diagonally over the nonamer (44 ̊) than the decamer (29 ̊). Other than CDR3alpha, each CDR loop remains in the same conformation. Thus, DMF4 engages the nonameric and decameric MART-1/HLA-A2 complexes with geometries that differ predominantly by a rigid-body rotation over the pMHC, with the pivot point of rotation centered on CDR3ß. The different geometries by which DMF4 binds the nonamer and decamer complexes result in different contacts made by various CDR loop amino acids to positions on HLA-A2.  A detailed list of contacts is given in Figure 2 and Supplemental Fig. 2.

Comments: The structures of the DMF4 TCR bound to the MART-1 nonamer (this structure) and decamer [PDB: 3QDM] peptide/HLA-A2 complexes showed that the TCR binds the two ligands differently. When the HLA-A2 peptide-binding domains in the two structures are superimposed, the root mean square deviation (RMSD) between the TCR variable domains is 5.1 Å. Viewed from the top through the TCR, each loop, with the exception of CDR3ß, is arranged differently over the pMHCs. This is reflected in a 15 ̊ difference in docking angle, with the TCR positioned more diagonally over the nonamer (44 ̊) than the decamer (29 ̊). Other than CDR3alpha, each CDR loop remains in the same conformation. Thus, DMF4 engages the nonameric and decameric MART-1/HLA-A2 complexes with geometries that differ predominantly by a rigid-body rotation over the pMHC, with the pivot point of rotation centered on CDR3ß. The different geometries by which DMF4 binds the nonamer and decamer complexes result in different contacts made by various CDR loop amino acids to positions on HLA-A2.  A detailed list of contacts is given in Figure 2 and Supplemental Fig. 2.

Comments: Unlike DMF4, the DMF5 TCR binds the MART-1 nonamer (this structure) and decamer [PDB: 3QDG] peptide/HLA-A2 complexes identically. In the two DMF5 complexes, the backbones of the TCR Valpha/Vß domains, common residues of the peptides, and the HLA-A2 peptide-binding domains superimpose with an RMSD of only 0.5 Å, and the conformations of the CDR loops are the same.  As expected from the near-identical structures, the participation of HLA-A2 amino acids in the two DMF5 interfaces is essentially the same. A detailed list of contacts is given in Figure 2 and Supplemental Fig. 2.

Comments: The DD31 TCR docked 75° across the long axis of the HLA-B*0801 Ag-binding cleft, consistent with previous TCR–pHLA docking modes. The center of mass of the Valpha- and the Vbeta-chains showed that the TCR docked over the N-terminal end of the Ag-binding cleft; nevertheless, the 13-residue–long CDR3beta loop stretched out to make contact with the C-terminal of the peptide as well. The DD31 TCR contacted all of the solvent accessible residues of HSK, thereby displaying maximal coverage of this epitope. The HSK peptide interacted only with the CDR3 loops, with the CDR3alpha loop contacting P1-H, P2-S, and P4-K and CDR3beta contacts P4-K, P6-C, P7-D, and P8-E. Comparison of the unliganded structure of HLA-B*0801–HSK [PDB: 4QRQ] and its complex with the DD31 TCR (this structure) showed that the HLA-B*0801 molecule did not change conformation appreciably upon TCR ligation. The peptide backbone also did not undergo major conformational changes upon TCR ligation, although three solvent accessible side chains (P1-H,  P6-C and P8-E) changed their conformation. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table II.

Comments: The MEL5 TCR bound in a canonical diagonal docking mode at a crossing angle of ∼47°, with shape complementarity and buried surface area within the range described for other published TCR-pMHC interactions. Superposition of the MEL5-A2-ELA [PDB: 3HG1] and MEL5-A2-EAA structures, using the MHC molecule to align, demonstrated a similar-binding conformation with the TCR CDR loops positioned identically over the MHC-binding groove. The contact footprint of the TCR over both surfaces was also similar, but not identical, with MEL5 contacting more residues on the surface of A2-EAA than A2-ELA. Concordantly, the TCR residues utilized for binding were very similar in each case, but again more TCR residues were involved in binding to A2-EAA than A2-ELA. The weaker anchor residue at position 2 in the natural peptide enabled the TCR to “pull” the peptide away from the MHC peptide-binding groove. This small movement facilitated nine extra contacts with the peptide, and indirectly led to 14 extra contacts with the MHC surface compared to the MEL5-A2-ELA interaction. These extra bonds explain the stronger binding affinity for the MEL5-A2-EAA interaction. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table S1.

This mode of recognition differed markedly from type I NKT TCR–CD1d–alpha-GalCer recognition [PDB: 2PO6], whereupon the Valpha24-Vbeta11 TCR sat parallel over the F′ pocket of CD1d. Accordingly, the interatomic contacts and roles of the individual CDR loops at the type I NKT TCR–CD1d–alpha-GalCer interface were markedly different to those at the 9B4 TCR–CD1d–alpha-GalCer interface. Compared to the unligated 9B4 TCR structure [PDB: 4WNQ], the 9B4 TCR variable regions did not significantly change conformation, however, the positioning of the constant regions was significantly altered by approximately a 17° shift in the elbow angle between the V and C domains in a direction toward the F′ pocket of CD1d. In contrast, there was minimal change in the conformation of the CDR loops upon ligation. Contacts are provided in Table S2.

Comments: The crystal structures of the trimolecular TCR–pMHC complex for two microbial peptides (this structure with PMM and [PDB: 4MAY] with UL15) that activated Hy.1B11 T cells were compared to the structure with the MBP peptide [PDB: 3PL6]. Each of the microbial peptides shared three residues with the MBP peptide, which included P3 Phe (both UL15 and PMM), P1 Val and P2 His (UL15) as well as P5 Lys and P8 Val (PMM). The position of the conserved P3 Phe within the DQ1 binding groove was very similar among the three trimolecular complexes. The peptides also shared a positive charge at P5. Outside this core region, the three peptides differed substantially in their sequence as well as the conformation of particular segments. For example, the MBP and PMM peptides showed notable differences in the conformation of the N-terminal (P1–P3) peptide segment. The interaction of Hy.1B11 TCR with MBP and microbial peptides was characterized by a striking feature, the deep insertion of the CDR3alpha F95 side chain into a pocket created by the P2, P3 and P5 peptide residues. Contacts are provided in Table 1 and Table S2.

Despite clear differences in both length and amino acid composition of the CDR3alpha and CDR3beta loops present in the L3-12, S13, and previously described SP3.4 [PDB: 4GG6] TCRs, the structures of these TCRs in complex with HLA-DQ8-glia-alpha1 revealed highly similar footprints and docking angles onto HLA-DQ8-glia-alpha1, as well as overall buried surface areas (BSA) of ∼900 Å^2. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 2.

Comments: The structure of the TRAV8-3/TRBV6-1 T316 TCR-HLA-DQ8-glia-alpha1 complex was compared to that of the TRBV9+ TCRs (SP3.4 [PDB: 4GG6], L3-12 [PDB: 4Z7V] and S13 [PDB: 4Z7U]). The overall docking orientation of this TRBV6-1+ TCR was similar to that of the TRBV9+ TCRs, but the center of mass was shifted toward the N terminus of the peptide, and the interface BSA of 1150 Å^2 was ∼25% larger compared with the TRBV9+ TCRs. However, the relative BSA contributions of the T316 TCR alpha-chain and beta-chain (45% and 55%, respectively) and the CDR3 loops (∼21% for CDR3alpha and 29% for CDR3beta) were broadly similar to those of the TRBV9+ TCRs (∼23% for CDR3alpha and 30% for CDR3beta). Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 3.

Comments: The crystal structures of five glycosphingolipids (GSLs) in complex with mouse CD1d and the mouse Valpha14Vbeta8.2 TCR were compared. The overall structures of all complexes [PDB: 4Y4F, 4Y4H, 4Y16, 4Y4K, 4Y2D] were consistent with the previously crystallized CD1d-glycolipid-TCR complexes, with the TCR docked offset over the F' pocket of CD1d in a parallel orientation to the two alpha helices, notably different from the diagonal footprint generated in MHC-peptide-TCR complexes. All GSLs bind with the fatty acid chain in the A' pocket of CD1d, the sphingoid base nestles inside the F' pocket and the galactose moiety exposed at the CD1d binding groove portal for TCR recognition. The contact surfaces between CD1d and the TCR are very similar throughout the different ternary complexes. All the TCR interactions with the antigen are formed with the conserved TCR alpha chain, while both TCR chains contact CD1d.

Comments: The crystal structures of five glycosphingolipids (GSLs) in complex with mouse CD1d and the mouse Valpha14Vbeta8.2 TCR were compared. The overall structures of all complexes [PDB: 4Y4F, 4Y4H, 4Y16, 4Y4K, 4Y2D] were consistent with the previously crystallized CD1d-glycolipid-TCR complexes, with the TCR docked offset over the F' pocket of CD1d in a parallel orientation to the two alpha helices, notably different from the diagonal footprint generated in MHC-peptide-TCR complexes. All GSLs bind with the fatty acid chain in the A' pocket of CD1d, the sphingoid base nestles inside the F' pocket and the galactose moiety exposed at the CD1d binding groove portal for TCR recognition. The contact surfaces between CD1d and the TCR are very similar throughout the different ternary complexes. All the TCR interactions with the antigen are formed with the conserved TCR alpha chain, while both TCR chains contact CD1d.

Comments: The TCR docks over the CD1d Ag binding groove in an orientation that is markedly different from the diagonal binding footprint seen in MHC–peptide–TCR complexes. As shown previously with models using the same TCR construct, the TCR interacts with CD1d using amino acids in the TCR CDR3alpha and CDR2ß loops, as well as a CDR3ß-dependent contact. There is well-defined density for the DB06-1 ligand, with the galactose head group exposed to recognition by the iNKT cell TCR. The binding orientation of DB06-1 within the hydrophobic A' and F' grooves of CD1d is also conserved, with the acyl chain localizing to the A' groove and the sphingoid base to the F' groove, with minimal to no differences when superimposed on the alphaGalCer–CD1d structure.

Comments: In the TCR-pMHC complex, the FS18 (this structure) and FS17 [PDB: 4Y1A] TCRs docked with the TCR alpha-chain positioned over the HLA-DR4 alpha-chain, whereas the TCR beta-chain was located over the HLA-DR4 beta-chain. The mode of FS18 TCR–pMHC class II docking was very similar to that of the FS17 TCR ternary complex. Thus, the orientation of the FS18 and FS17 TCRs are reversed through 180° compared to all previously determined ternary TCR-pMHC complexes. The FS18 and FS17 TCRs made limited contacts with the HLA-DR4 molecule; this was consistent with the extremely weak affinity of the FS18 and FS17 TCR-HLA-DR4-epitope interaction. The FS18 TCR beta-chain solely contacted HLA-DR4-epitope, ligating to a few residues on the HLA-DR4alpha chain and HLA-DR4beta chain. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 2.
